					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I usually reserve a page of ROM for values $00-$ff, so if I wanted I could do the following to increment X by 4:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; lda ByteTable+4, x<br />&nbsp; tax</div><br />This is a little faster than INX x4 (6 cycles vs. 8) while also occupying 4 bytes, but I definitely wouldn't use 256 bytes of ROM just for this. This table has many other uses though, such as simulating TXY (&quot;ldy ByteTable, x&quot;) and TYX (&quot;ldx ByteTable, y&quot;) instructions, in addition to the quick increments/decrements by constant numbers to index registers.<br /><br />Many would consider this table a waste of space, but it has already made it possible for me to avoid temporary variables and also write slightly faster code in loops (thus saving a significant amount of cycles), by making the index registers more capable than usual.</div><br /><br />What a neat tip! I don't mind wasting space, PRG is cheap compared to other things one can waste on the NES.</div>

